To be honest, I was hesitant to go on a safari trip. I do my best to practice what I preach and to treat animals as equals. I’ve seen the repulsive videos and documentation of exploitation of these animals in this part of the world and it made me sick. I didn’t want to contribute to that.

But first some back story: I am currently in Kenya on assignment with @brittanygawley and @jemu_mwenda capturing video on a safari conservation trip guided by @jemuexpeditions.

After learning more about the work both Brittany and James have done, it became more clear what my reason was and how deeply their mission aligned with me. 

They made this trip in the spirit of conservation; to experience the beauty of Africa while at the same time travelling slowly, respectfully and mindfully. 

We are visiting sanctuaries instead of zoos. We are driving on sanctioned roads through parks instead of off-roading which disturbed the animals and flora and fauna. We are staying in more sustainable camps that have been built around nature instead of through it. Proceeds from these trips are going to the pockets of Kenyan’s instead of international tour companies.

And to top it off, we are guided by two people who have dedicated their lives to improving the way safaris are done.

To say I am proud and honoured to join them is an understatement.

During our visit to Amboseli, we got to visit a traditional Maasai village one afternoon. The first photo shows a family and the clay houses they live in. The second a bedroom with a small window. Third, a kid hanging on a tree as we were leaving and fourth, a welcome song and dance. Captured on assignment in Kenya with @jemuexpeditions and @brittanygawley.
Kenya, 2023

Ol Pejeta Conservancy, Kenya, 2023

Captured on assignment with @brittanygawley and @jemuexpeditions.

Asante-sana Kenya. Will always remember these cool evenings with the purr of the Land Cruiser, “African massage” of the bumpy gravel roads and orange skies dotted with silhouettes of animals I’ve always dreamed of.

When @salomon asked me to photograph a runner of my choice, I knew I wanted to do something different. I chose to feature the person who inspires me most. I chose my mom.

I invited her on a trip to British Columbia, to experience the beauty of running in the mountains for the first time. And at age 70 - without any hesitation, she said yes.

“Those who are fearless never grow old.”

@thenorthface / Trailwear S2023

Athlete: @run.ride.reflect 
Assist: @samboppart 
Video legends: @johnpatkelly @matthew_carew_photography 
Photo: @ me

Really stoked for the launch of The Art of Running film series today with @salomonrunning.

Most of who we see in run media are young, fast and elite athletes - as a photographer I get it. It’s easier to shoot, less risk, the strides are long and smooth and it sells.

But there is a large percentage of runners that are under represented due to many circumstances, including their age. 

When Salomon asked me to choose a runner to photograph, the first person that came to mind was my mom.

She is the truest definition of a lifelong athlete and lover of the sport. She tracks her weekly mileage down to the decimal, stretches and lifts weight to stay injury free, and signs up for new races every year.

My mom is the most badass person I know and the fact that she said yes to running in the alpine for the first time at age 70, says it all. She is my biggest inspiration as a photographer and runner and it means the world to me to share her story with a larger audience. 

Thank you @salomon for the assistance in sharing her story. Thank you @johnpatkelly and @matthew_carew_photography for bringing the story to life.

POV: living out your trail running dreams with your best friend in California. 

Catherine and I spent a week road tripping around Northern California in a camper van, seeking the most epic trails in the area, here are 3 of our favourites in the region:

1) Dipsea Trail - known as the oldest trail race in America, dating back to 1905, this trail begins in Mill Valley and ends in Stinson Beach, the perfect place to have a drink, swim and relax post-run. You can start and end at Stinson Beach and link this trail with Steep Ravine and Matt Davis to form a 13km loop with 600m of elevation gain. #visitmarin
 
2) Salt Point Trail - this is the perfect 5km out and back trail to experience the beauty of this untouched coastline with very little elevation gain. Bonus: at the halfway point, the trail brings you down to Stump Beach Cove, the perfect spot to have a swim and a definitely little hidden gem!

3) Meadow and Vista Trail in Sugarloaf Ridge - this is a fantastic intermediate trail run, offering a lot of “bang for buck” in terms of views with a distance of 7km and 250m of elevation. There is a lot of sun exposure so best to run early in the day while it’s still cool. We ran this trail from our campsite so if you camp in the State Park you don’t even have to drive to the trailhead!

Save this video and check out @visitcalifornia to plan your next trail running trip!

#ad #visitcalifornia

Some places just beg you to slow down and appreciate the little things.. as if you’re a child experiencing everything for the first time all over again. 

Fueling our days with a morning trail run, followed by an afternoon wine tasting, and an evening ocean dip - made me feel that childlike sense of wonder and play everyday. 

Surrounded by untouched coastline, world-class trails, and old-growth redwood forest, Northern California is truly a trail runner’s dream come true. 

@visitcalifornia #visitcalifornia #ad

Nothing makes me feel more connected to myself than spending time outdoors trail running. There’s something about the primal nature of moving through the forest, mountains and coastlines that just hits you deep in your soul. The feeling of physical effort, exhaustion, of doing nothing for the rest of the day except lying in the back of the van, staring out into the ocean.. and being okay with it. 

My favourite form of travel is, no doubt, on foot and through trails. You get to see all parts of a place, and not just what “wants to be seen”. The experience feels more intimate, unfiltered and personal. I have dirt underneath my fingernails, sweat all over my clothes, a slight sunburn on my skin, and a proud soreness from the topography of the land in my muscles.

I end up bringing home far more than I sought. A sense of belonging, of identity, and of community. Out of the many incredible adventures @visitcalifornia has to offer, trail running is my favourite.

#visitcalifornia #ad

Excerpt from @5peaksrun production “Way Out Beyond” which premieres this weekend as we celebrate family & community!

“It might be over soon.”

Reminder from @thislisasweetman that everything in life might be over soon - the good & the bad.

Excerpt from @5peaksrun production “Way Out Beyond” by @adamstevensvisuals scheduled to premiere this weekend.

“Way Out Beyond” is an inspiring and deeply personal short film that celebrates the power of running, resilience, and the unwavering spirit of Lisa Sweetman as she triumphs over adversity and uses her experiences to empower others. It beautifully illustrates how physical activity and a supportive community can help forge an unbreakable spirit within us all.

More than a race series, we are proud of the members of our community like Lisa, who over the past 25 years have created an inclusive space for thousands of runners of all ages, abilities and ambitions to experience trail running.
